TY  - JOUR
T1  - Adverse Risk Incentives and the Design of Performance-Based Contracts
AU  - Grinblatt, Mark
AU  - Titman, Sheridan
Y1  - 1989/07/01
PY  - 1989
DA  - 1989/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.35.7.807
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.35.7.807
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 807
EP  - 822
VL  - 35
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper uses option pricing theory to value and analyze many performance-based fee contracts that are currently in use. A potential problem with some of these contracts is that they may induce portfolio managers to adversely alter the risk of the portfolios they manage. The paper is prescriptive in that it presents conditions for contract parameters that provide proper risk incentives for classes of investment strategies. For buy-and-hold and rebalancing strategies adverse risk incentives are avoided when the penalties for poor performance outweigh the rewards for good performance.
